Complex game systems are notoriously difficult to tame. An unbalanced game feels broken, but staring at a blank database trying to intuit the perfect mana cost for a spell is a recipe for analysis paralysis. While playtesting is the ultimate arbiter of truth, you need a starting point. My approach is to retreat to the safety of spreadsheets and establish a "Standard Currency." This doesn't need to be actual in-game gold; it can be abstract, like "Turns required to acquire" or "Damage per Action." By converting every card, unit, or resource into this single standardized value, you can mathematically compare a movement speed buff against a fireball and establish a baseline of fairness.

However, don't let the math freeze you. An unbalanced but playable prototype is infinitely better than a blank spreadsheet waiting for "perfect" numbers. Pick a value, plug it in, and see if it breaks. You can always adjust the variables later, but you cannot test a system that doesn't exist. There are advanced tricks for decision modeling and probability that can refine this later, but the priority is simply getting the machine running.

There is, however, a danger in being too good at the math. I once spent weeks balancing a complex economy, ensuring every strategy had the exact same expected value and win probability. The result was a technically perfect game where every card felt exactly the sameâ€”and it was incredibly boring. True fun often lives in the outliers. Once your system is mathematically sound, you must intentionally throw curveballs. Create items that are slightly Overpowered (OP); introduce spikes in difficulty. Use the math to create the rules, then break them to create the excitement.
